WHY PV & PVC EXISTS?

>> Problem with Pods
Pods are emphemeral that is temporary
When pod dies --> data is lost
Pod deleted → container gone → data gone 

>> Solution is Persistent Storage
Data should live outside the Pod Lifecycle

Pod → PVC → PV → Actual Storage (Disk / Cloud)

PERSISTENT VOLUME (PV)

>> A PersistentVolume (PV) is a piece of storage in the cluster that has been provisioned by an administrator or dynamically provisioned using Storage Classes.

>> PVs are resources in the cluster.

>> PV is an actual storage in the cluster (like a disk)

>> Think of it as AWS EBS, GCP Persistent Disk, Azure Disk, NFS, Local Disk

PERSISTENT CLAIM VOLUME (PVC)

>> A PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) is a request for storage by a user. It is similar to a Pod. Pods consume node resources and PVCs consume PV resources. 

>> A PVC is a request for storage made by a Pod
>> think of it as "I need 1GB storage"

HOW PV AND PVC WORK TOGETHER

1. Admin creates PV (storage available)
2. Developer creates PVC (request)
3. K8S (control plane/ Persistent controller) matches PVC-->PV
4. Pod uses PVC

PVC request → Kubernetes binds → PV


PV & PVC LIFECYCLE

1. Provisioning (How storage is created)

>> Static Provisioning (Manual way)
Admin creates storage in advance
Admin creates multiple PVs
example :
10Gi PV, 50Gi PV, 100Gi PV
Users (developers) can later claim them

>> Dynamic Provisioning (Automatic Way)
Happens when there is no matching PV exists
Instead of faiing, k8s says: "okay, ill create a storage for you"
How??
PVC must mention a StorageClass
That StorageClass has a Provisioner (like AWS EBS)
the administrator must have created and configured that class for dynamic provisioning to occur.

>> to enable dynamic storage provisioning bases on storage class, the cluster admin needs to enable"DefaultStorageClass"admission controller on the API server.

Control Plane sees PVC
No matching PV found
Calls provisioner
New PV is created automatically

***Claims that request class "" disable dynamic provisioning***

If PVC says: storageClassName: ""
Kubernetes will NOT create storage automatically
Only existing PVs will be considered

>> DefaultStorageClass admission controller

>> Binding
What actually happens --- 
User creates PVC
Control Plane detects it
It tries to find a matching PV

>> Matching Rules?
+ PV size >= PVC request
+ Access modes match
+ StorageClass match

>> Binding Happens---
Once matched : PV ↔ PVC are linked (bound)
+ One-to-One mapping
+ Exclusive

If PV was created just for that PVC, it will always bind to that same PVC

>> If No matching PV exists
PVC stays in : Pending state
until a matching PV is created


STEPS

1. Creation of PV
PV is created either:
+ Statically by admin
+ Dynamically via StorageClass
PV represents the actual storage (disk, EBS,NFS)

2. Creation of PVC
User creates PVC specifying
+ Required storage (eg 10Gi)
+ Access mode
+ StorageClass
PVC is only a request, not actual storage

3. Binding of PVC to PV
K8S Control Plane (PV Controller)
+ Watches for new PVCs
+ Searches for matching PV

Matching Criteria:
PV capacity ≥ PVC request
Access modes match
StorageClass matches

>> If Match found : PVC is bound to PV, Binding is one-to-one

>> If No Match  : PVC remains in Pending State
If StorageClass exists → Dynamic provisioning happens

4. Internal Mapping
After Binding
PVC (my-pvc) → PV (actual storage)
This mapping is stored internally using:
claimRef in PV

5. Pod Definition (Using PVC)
Pod does not use PV directly
Pod refers PVC in yaml
volumes:
- name: storage
  persistentVolumeClaim:
    claimName: my-pvc

6. Pod Creation and Scheduling
Pod is created and scheduled to a Node
K8s checks does PVC exits and Is PVC in Bound State?

7. Kubelet Mount Process (Actual Execution)
On the Node:
Kubelet performs:
Reads Pod spec
Identifies PVC
Finds bound PV
Contacts storage backend
Attaches disk (if needed)
Mounts volume to node
Mounts inside container

8. Volume inside Container 
volume is mounted at
mountpath (..../data)
Application accesses storage via this path

Pod → uses PVC only
PVC → linked to one PV
Binding is exclusive (1:1)
PV is cluster-level, PVC is namespace-level

1. PV created (static/dynamic)
2. PVC created (user request)
3. Control Plane binds PVC ↔ PV
4. Pod references PVC
5. Kubernetes resolves PVC → PV
6. Kubelet mounts storage
7. Container uses storage via mountPath


PV YAML FILE
 
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: pv1
spec:  
  capacity:
    storage: 5Gi
  accessModes:
   - ReadWriteOnce
  hostPath:
    path: /data

accessModes
ReadWriteOnce (RWO) One node can mount
ReadOnlyMany (ROX)
ReadWriteMany (RWX)  Multiple nodes can mount

hostPath → only for testing
Production → use cloud storage

PVC YAML FILE

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: pvc
spec:
  accessmode: 
   - ReadWriteOnce
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 1Gi

POD ---> PVC

volumes:
 - name : storage
   persistentVolumeClaim:
     claimName: pvc

Mount inside container

volumeMounts:
 - mountPath: /data
   name: storage

/data inside container → actual disk storage

STORAGE CLASS

>> k8s resource that defines how storage should be dynamically created.

>> StorageClass = Template/Blueprint for creating PersistentVolumes dynamically

Before StorageClass:
Admin had to manually create PVs 
Not scalable 

After StorageClass:
Storage is created automatically when PVC is requested 
Fully automated system 

PVC → StorageClass → Provisioner → PV → Pod

| Feature    | PV             | PVC              |
| ---------- | -------------- | ---------------- |
| Role       | Storage        | Request          |
| Created by | Admin / System | User             |
| Lifecycle  | Independent    | Bound to Pod     |
| Example    | Disk           | Request for disk |


RECLAIM POLICY

>> Reclaim Policy defines what happens to a PersistentVolume (PV) after its PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) is deleted.

>>Reclaim Policy = What to do with storage after user releases it

>> types of Reclaim Policies

1. Delete  PVC deleted → PV deleted → Disk deleted
2. Retain  PVC deleted → PV stays → Data stays → Manual action needed
3. Recycle   wipe (deprecated)

reclaimPolicy: Retain

PV = storage  
PVC = request  
Pod = uses storage via PVC  

No PVC → No persistence  
PVC → Data survives Pod  